        <name>16.5.4.2 Find the Taylor series</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What is the Taylor series of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\dfrac{1}{1-x}\)&lt;/span&gt; about &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(x=2\)&lt;/span&gt;. (That is, find a power series in powers of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\((x-2)\)&lt;/span&gt;.)&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;First, obtain the first three derivatives and the &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(n^{\text{th}}\)&lt;/span&gt; derivative of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(f(x)=\dfrac{1}{1-x}\)&lt;/span&gt;: &lt;span class="math display"&gt;\[f'(x)=\dfrac{1}{(1-x)^2},\qquad f''(x)=\dfrac{2}{(1-x)^3},\qquad f'''(x)=\dfrac{6}{(1-x)^4},\qquad
\cdots \quad f^{(n)}(x)=\dfrac{n!}{(1-x)^{n+1}}\]&lt;/span&gt; Now evaluate these derivatives at &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(x_0=2\)&lt;/span&gt;: &lt;span class="math display"&gt;\[f'(2)=1,\qquad f''(2)=-2,\qquad f'''(2)=6,\qquad f^{(n)}(2)=(-1)^{n+1}n!\]&lt;/span&gt; Hence, write down the Taylor expansion of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(f(x)=\dfrac{1}{1-x}\)&lt;/span&gt; about &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(x=2\)&lt;/span&gt;: &lt;span class="math display"&gt;\[\dfrac{1}{1-x}=-1+(x-2)-(x-2)^2+(x-2)^3+\cdots + (-1)^{n+1}(x-2)^n+\cdots\]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
        <generalfeedbackformat>1</generalfeedbackformat>
        <defaultmark>1.0000000</defaultmark>
        <penalty>0.3333333</penalty>
